    "complete Heyting algebra) H and closure operator j, one obtains a new Heyting algebra (resp.",
    "complete Heyting algebra) H j by taking the fixed points of j in H, with the same meet and implication as in H, but with a new join defined by A + B = j(A ⊔ B), where ⊔ is the join in H. This is in essence what Beth semantics does.",
    "If P is full, then P together with ∩, ⊃, and + form the complete Heyting algebra H(S, ⊑) j.",
    "Even if P is not full, our requirement that P be closed under ∩, ⊃, and + guarantees that P gives rise to a subalgebra of H(S, ⊑) j and therefore a Heyting algebra.",
    "Finally, the second fact is important because if we form H j with j as double negation, then H j is a Boolean algebra, which is complete if H is complete."
